@supercharleszhu unfortunately export is device specific, although maybe you haven't run into those cases yet. For example if your code had something like:
```
def f(x):
    return torch.ones(3, device=x.device)
```
Then the graph would hardcode the device of your sample input x into the graph. Thats why we added the `move_to_device_pass` to help "cast" the entire graph to the device. 

Separately, if you do want to remove the asserts, you can use this [_RemoveRuntimeAssertionsPass](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/d746b987d8239595438b9dbd0f96ec6a4fed4653/torch/_export/passes/remove_runtime_assertions.py#L4) pass -- you can call it via `_RemoveRuntimeAssertionsPass(exported_program.graph_module)` or `_RemoveRuntimeAssertionsPass(exported_program.module())`

